@node Einleitung "Introduction"

MathScript is a formula editor, which is used to integrate mathematical
formulas into word processors. In principle this is nothing new but untill
now it was a deficit for the Amiga. Although it is possible to create such
formulas with TeX, it is not very convenient.@{par}

That is why MathScript was created.@{par}

With this program it is very easy to create complex formulas. Use of vector
fonts garantees high quality. To insert the formulas into word processors or
DTP programs they are saved as graphics files.@{par}

These are the features of version 2.1:@{par}

- extensive amount of mathematical and physical symbols@{par}
- Control codes for formatting (super-, subscript, fractions, roots)@{par}
- easy input with @{"MUI" link MUI}@{par}
- Export in the following formats:@{par}
        EPS@{par}
        Binary EPS (EPS with TIFF preview@{par}
        IFF_ILBM@{par}
        TIFF@{par}
- Import of exported files@{par}
- Preview of the formula in any resolution@{par}
- adjustable fore- and background color for exported files.@{par}
- Online Help (AmigaGuide + GadgetHelp)@{par}
- ARexx port@{par}
- ARexx scripts on function keys@{par}
- support for the locale.library (beginning with OS 2.1).@{par}
    Available languages: english,deutsch,français,svenska,suomi,dansk.@{par}
    You may also create your own languages (see @{"Catalogs/readme" link "MathScript:Catalogs/readme/MAIN"}).
- AppWindow/AppIcon support@{par}
- Automatic generation of icons@{par}

@endnode

@node System-Anforderungen "System requirements"

Minimum:@{par}

  OS 2.0@{par}
  @{"MUI" link MUI} 2.2@{par}
  1MB RAM@{par}

Recommended:@{par}

  OS 2.1, better: 3.x@{par}
  @{"MUI" link MUI} 2.3@{par}
  1.5MB RAM@{par}
  68020 CPU@{par}

Furthermore the post.library is needed. It is included in this software
package.@{par}


@endnode

@node Start "Starting the program"

Starting MathScript ...@{par}

  from the @{b}Workbench:@{ub}@{par}

To start MathScript from the Workbench enter the directory where the program
is installed and double click its icon. @{par}
Alternativly you can click on an icon of a previously saved formula to start
MathScript loading this formula automaticaly.@{par}

  from the @{b}Shell:@{ub}@{par}

To launch MathScript from the Shell type in "MathScript:MathScript".
The following arguments are accepted:@{par}
  @{b}FILE@{ub}@{par}

FILE : name of a formula which shall be loaded immediately@{par}

@endnode

@node FirstSteps "First Steps"

This chapter offers you a short introduction to MathScript.@{par}
If you are not familiar with it, read this chapter page by page.@{par}
While reading about a topic it is the best to practice it with the program at once. Therefore start MathScript.@{par}

@{"Let's go!" link Go}

@endnode

@node Go "The main window"

@{b}The main window@{ub}@{par}

After you have started MathScript the @{"main window" link mainwin} will appear.
It is subdivided into four parts:@{par}

1. The @{"Toolbar" link Toolbar}@{par}
2. The @{"Selection gadgets" link Select}@{par}
3. The @{"Input gadget" link Input}@{par}
4. The @{"Preview area" link Preview}@{par}

We will first concentrate on the input gadget.@{par}

@{"Next page" link Inp}

@endnode

@node Inp "Writing the formula"

@{b}Writing the formula@{ub}@{par}

For writing the formulas into MathScript the @{"input gadget" link Input} is used.@{par}
The input is made with the keyboard or with the @{"selection gadgets" link Select}.@{par}
Formatting functions are specified by special @{"control codes" link Codes},
thus without WYSIWYG representation.@{par}

To enter standard ASCII letters the keyboard is used while the input gadget is
active.@{par}

We will now create our first formula. Type the following string into the input
gadget: "x=1/2" (without quotation marks!)@{par}

@{"Next page" link ShowPreview}

@endnode

@node ShowPreview "Preview of the formula"

@{b}Preview of the formula@{ub}@{par}

Now we want to show the formula. We use the @{"Preview area" link Preview} for that purpose@{par}
Click into the big empty area. By that the preview is activated. Untill the formula
is shown, you may have to wait some seconds. The first time you show the preview,
it will take more time because the PostScript font has to be loaded first.@{par}

In our example the following should appear in the preview area:@{par}
  1@{par}
x=-@{par}
  2@{par}

@{"Next page" link Format}

@endnode

@node Format "Formatting the formula"

@{b}Formatting the formula@{ub}@{par}

In order to format a formula, which means to change the size and position
of certain parts, @{"Control codes" link Codes} are used.@{par}
In our first example we already have used such a control code: the character '/'.
It causes a fraction.@{par}

Its @{b}Syntax@{ub} is:@{par}

@{b}Fraction:@{ub}@{par}
  @{b}syntax:@{ub} <Obj1>/<Obj2>@{par}
  @{b}function:@{ub} Creates a fraction.@{par}
  @{b}input:@{ub} <Obj1> - nominator@{par}
           <Obj2> - denominator@{par}

Each control codes needs @{"objects" link Objects}. Following the syntax above, this
control code needs two objects, namely a nominator and a denominator.@{par}
Thus in our example <Obj1> was '1' and <Obj2> was '2'.@{par}

A complete overview of all supported control codes together with their syntax
can be found in @{"control codes" link Codes}.@{par}

@{"Next page" link Objects}

@endnode

@node Objects

The @{"control codes" link Codes} need objects. Such an object is in the simplest
case a single character.@{par}

So writing "1/2x" results in the following illustration:@{par}
  1@{par}
  - x@{par}
  2@{par}
But if you wish the denominator to be 2x, thus using more than one character,
you have to group it to a single object. This is done by surrounding the
concerning characters by @{b}brackets@{ub}.@{par}
So 1/[2x] causes the following term:@{par}
   1@{par}
  --@{par}
  2x@{par}
Of course it is possible to create a grouped object inside of another grouped
object. To create a double fraction simply write [1/x]/3 which results in the
following:@{par}
   1@{par}
   -@{par}
   x@{par}
  ---@{par}
   3

@{"Next page" link Sel}

@endnode

@node Sel "The Selection Gadgets"

@{b}The Selection Gadgets@{ub}@{par}

Although one can use all @{"control codes" link Codes} with the keyboard,
it is not very convenient to have all of them in mind.@{par}
Moreover MathScript has a variety of special mathematical and physical
sysmbols, which are not available by the keyboard.@{par}
To use such symbols and control codes in an easy way, the @{"Selection Gadgets" link Select}
are used.@{par}

There are 13 such gadgets.@{par}
If you click on one of them, a window will pop up below, which is divided into
single fields. These fields are covered with different symbols. If you keep
the mouse button pressed you can select one of them. When you release the 
button the corresponding symbol will be inserted into the @{"input gadget" link Input}.
If you do not want to select one, simply release the button if no one is
selected.@{par}
Furthermore you can control these gadgets with the keyboard. Use the tab key to
select the active gadget, press return and use the cursor keys to highlight
the desired symbol, then press return again to insert it, press space to close
the menu without insertion.@{par}
You can also use the keys <right Amiga> <1> - <6> to pop up the lower gadgets and
<right Amiga> <shift> <1> - <7> to pop up the gadgets above.@{par}

Beside simple characters @{"control codes" link Codes} can be inserted, too.
They are shown in a symbolic representation and not in the way they are
written. @{par}
The @{"objects" link Objects} belonging to them are symbolized in the following
manner:@{par}
– stands for a grouped object,@{par}
# for a single character.@{par}

@{b}Example:@{ub}@{par}
            –@{par}
The symbol #  means superscript. It inserts the following text into the
@{"input gadget" link Input}: ^[] .@{par}
Lets's suppose there is a single x standing behind the cursor. After clicking
on the symbol the contents of the input gadget becomes like this: x^[].
The cursor is placed automatically behind the first grouped @{"object" link Objects},
so behind the '['. By pressing the key '2' the text is "x^[2]", which leads to
this "picture": x˛.@{par}
But if the first object is a grouped one, you have to select its gadget first
and type in its text afterwards in order to be placed between the brackets
(see @{"objects" link Objects}).

@{"Next page" link LoadSave}

@endnode

@node LoadSave "Load, Save, Export"

@{b}Load, Save, Export@{ub}@{par}

You should be able to create rather complex formulas now.@{par}
If you have created one and it lokks in the preview like you have imagined,
you should save it now.@{par}
Therefore select the menu item @{"Save as..." link SaveAs} in the "Project"
menu.@{par}
If you have already saved or loaded a formula, you can save the current under
the same name by selecting the menu item @{"Save" link Save}.@{par}
With the menu item @{"Load..." link Load} you can load a previously saved
formula. The same is possible by dragging an icon of a formula over the
@{"main window" link mainwin}.@{par}

So called FML files are used by Load/Save. These are only useable with MathScript
and contain only the formula description which is written in the @{"input gadget" link Input}.@{par}
In order to use the formulas in other applications, they have to be exported
in a @{"graphic format" link GfxTypes}.@{par}
Therefore use the menu item @{"Export..." link Export}. It contains additional
submenu items with which you can chose the @{"graphic format" link GfxTypes}.@{par}


Well, that's it! You should have acquired the basic skills to use MathScript.
The following chapters go more into details.@{par}

Back to the @{"Contents" link Main}.

@endnode


@node mainwin "Main Window"

The Main Window is subdivided into the following regions:@{par}

@{"Toolbar" link Toolbar}@{par}

@{"Selection Gadgets" link Select}@{par}

@{"Input gadget" link Input}@{par}

@{"Preview area" link Preview}@{par}

@{"Quick Help" link quickhelp}@{par}

@endnode

@node Toolbar

You can access the most wanted menu items with this toolbar, namely:@{par}

@{"New" link New} @{par}
@{"Load" link Load} @{par}
@{"Save" link Save} @{par}

@{"Import" link Import} @{par}
@{"Export" link Export} @{par}

@{"Start ARexx script" link StartARexx} @{par}

@{"Change Settings" link ChangeSettings} @{par}

@{"Zoom" link Zoom} @{par}

@endnode

@node Zoom

Here you can set the zoom level of the @{"Preview" link Preview}.@{par}
With this it is possible to change the size of the preview without changing
the settings.@{par}
All numbers are in percent (max. 3 digits). With the popup gadget you can
select some of the most used zoom levels.

@endnode


@node Select "Selection Gadgets"

There are the following selection gadgets:@{par}

@{"operators" link sel1} @{"arrows" link sel2} @{"logic" link sel3} @{"brackets" link sel4} @{"sum,prod,int" link sel5} @{"greek chars" link sel6} @{"GREEK CHARS" link sel7}@{par}

@{"equations" link sel8} @{"theory of sets" link sel9} @{"symbols" link sel10} @{"super-/subscript" link sel11} @{"fraction,root" link sel12} @{"derivatives" link sel13} @{"Matrices" link sel14}@{par}

@endnode

@node sel1 "Operators"

Contains a collection of mathematical operators.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> <shift> 1'

@endnode

@node sel2 "Arrows"

There are 5 single and 5 double arrows.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> <shift> 2'

@endnode

@node sel3 "Logic"

Holds logical symbols.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> <shift> 3'

@endnode

@node sel4 "Brackets"

Includes @{"control codes" link Codes} for making brackets of variable size.
There are for each bracket type ({,(,[,],|,<) left and right sided versions
and brackets on both sides.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> <shift> 4'

@endnode

@node sel5 "sum,product und integral"

Three characters symbolizing a sum, product and an integral.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> <shift> 5'

@endnode

@node sel6 "small greek characters"

Contains all small greek characters.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> <shift> 6'

@endnode

@node sel7 "big greek characters"

Includes all greek characters.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> <shift> 7'

@endnode

@node sel8 "Equations"

Holds the most important equation and inequality symbols.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> 1'

@endnode

@node sel9 "symbols of the theory of sets"

A collection of symbols of the theory of sets.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> 2'

@endnode

@node sel10 "Symbols"

Includes symbols not belonging to other groups.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> 3'

@endnode

@node sel11 "Super-/subscript"

Contains all @{"control codes" link Codes} for positioning @{"objects" link Objects}.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> 4'

@endnode

@node sel12 "Fraction and root"

Holds @{"control codes" link Codes} for making fractions and roots.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> 5'

@endnode

@node sel13 "derivatives"

Contains @{"control codes" lonk Codes} for creating derivatives and vectors.@{par}

Keyboard shortcut: '<right Amiga> 6'

@endnode

@node sel14 "Matrices"

Several @{"control codes" link Codes} for different matrices.@{par}
The last symbol opens the @{"matrix window" link Matrixwin}, which is used to insert
any (m,n)-matrix.@{par}

@endnode

@node Matrixwin "Matrix Window"

You can chose any matrix in this window.@{par}

@{b}Rows@{ub}@{par}
  Enter the number of rows.@{par}
@{b}Columns@{ub}@{par}
  Enter the number of columns.@{par}

Click on "Ok" to insert this kind of matrix, else "Cancel".

@endnode


@node Input "Input gadget"

All formulas are typed into the input gadget.@{par}
It is a standard string gadget and therefore accepts all key short cuts,
which can be applied to other string gadgets.@{par}

Press <space> to activate it.
@endnode

@node Preview "Preview area"

In this area the preview of the current formula is displayed.@{par}
In order to generate such a preview just click on this area.@{par}

It may happen that the full formula cannot be displayed. Use the scroller gadgets
to adjust the visible area.

@endnode

@node quickhelp "Quick Help"

When you point your mouse over a gadget of the @{"Main Window" link mainwin} a short
help text will be displayed here.

@endnode

@node setwin "Settings Window"

The settings window can be opened by selecting the menu item @{"Change settings" link ChangeSettings}.@{par}

It is divided into four different "pages", namely:@{par}

@{"System" link SysSet}@{par}

@{"General" link GenSet}@{par}

@{"ARexx" link ARexxSet}@{par}

@{"Export" link ExpSet}@{par}

Moreover there is a seperate menu with the following items:@{par}
    @{"Reset to Defaults" link SetDef}@{par}
    @{"Last Saved" link SetLastSaved}@{par}
    @{"Restore" link SetRestore}@{par}

In order to leave the settings window, select "Ok" or "Cancel".

@endnode

@node SysSet "System Settings"

On this page you can set some options regarding the (operating) system.@{par}

@{b}Path@{ub}@{par}
With the small filerequester gadget or the string gadget you can specify a
path MathScript uses as a default for loading/saving.@{par}

@{b}No Icons@{ub}@{par}
If this option is not active MathScript will create suitable icons while
saving/exporting.@{par}
By replacing the icons in the drawer "icons" you can use your own icons.

@endnode

@node GenSet "General Settings"

On this page you can set general preferences.@{par}

@{b}Font size@{ub}@{par}
You are able to specify the font size in pt (1/72 inch) here.@{par}

@{b}Preview resolution@{ub}@{par}
Both gadgets can be used to set the x and y resolution of the preview in dpi
(dots per inch).@{par}

@{b}Colors@{ub}@{par}
You are able to specify the fore- and background colors here. There are
two pages for each color. OS 2.x users will get three slider gadgets there,
while OS 3.x users will get a colorwheel.@{par}
The colors are not used for the @{"Preview" link Preview}, but for the exported
files.@{par}
Note: The EPS based formats do not support the background color.


@endnode

@node ARexxSet "ARexx Settings"

You can place some ARexx scripts on your function keys on this page.@{par}

@{b}Function keys@{ub}@{par}
For each function key Fn (n=1,2,...,10) you can specify an ARexx script in
the string gadgets, which will be executed by pressing this key or selecting
the corresponding menu item @{"Fn: ..." link FKey}.@{par}
Pressing the PopUp gadgets on the right side will open an filerequester.@{par}

@{b}Only names@{ub}@{par}
You can specify wheter an ARexx script should appear in the "Arexx" menu only
with its name or with the full path.@{par}

@endnode

@node ExpSet "Export Settings"

You can set some options for the different @{"graphic formats" link GfxTypes} on this page.@{par}
It consists of some other pages which contain settings for a specific format,
namely:@{par}

@{"EPS" link SetEPS}@{par}

@{"Binary EPS" link SetBinEPS}@{par}

@{"IFF" link SetIFF}@{par}

@{"TIFF" link SetTIFF}@{par}

@endnode

@node SetEPS "EPS Settings"

There is only one option:@{par}

@{b}Include font@{ub}@{par}
If this option is activated the postscript description of the math font is
embedded into the EPS files. This is necessary if the postscript interpreter
is unable to load fonts from your harddisk. This applies of course to all
postscript printers. But if a application with a software interpreter
(Post, PostView, FinalWriter...) is used, it will look (with a suitable
init.ps file) in the directory PSFonts: after available fonts. So in this
case it is better not to include the font, so the size of your EPS files will
not grow too much.@{par}
If you want to use your formula on another computer you should activate this
option, because the font will not be available on other systems.

@endnode

@node SetBinEPS "Binary EPS Settings"

There are the following options regarding the "Binary EPS" format:@{par}

@{b}Include font@{ub}@{par}
If this option is activated the postscript description of the math font is
embedded into the EPS files. This is necessary if the postscript interpreter
is unable to load fonts from your harddisk. This applies of course to all
postscript printers. But if a application with a software interpreter
(Post, PostView, FinalWriter...) is used, it will look (with a suitable
init.ps file) in the directory PSFonts: after available fonts. So in this
case it is better not to include the font, so the size of your EPS files will
not grow too much.@{par}
If you want to use your formula on another computer you should activate this
option, because the font will not be available on other systems.@{par}

@{b}Preview resolution@{ub}@{par}
Both gadgets are used to specify the resolution in dpi of the preview part of
the EPS files.

@endnode

@node SetIFF "IFF Settings"

There is only one option available regarding the IFF format:@{par}

@{b}Resolution@{ub}@{par}
Both gadgets are used to specify the x and y resolution in dpi.

@endnode

@node SetTIFF "TIFF Settings"

There is only one option available regarding the TIFF format:@{par}

@{b}Resolution@{ub}@{par}
Both gadgets are used to specify the x and y resolution in dpi.

@endnode

@node SetDef "Reset to Defaults"

The default settings will be used.

@endnode

@node SetLastSaved "Last Saved"

The last saved settings will be loaded again.

@endnode

@node SetResore "Restore"

The settings will be set to the state they had after opening the @{"Settings Window" link setwin}.@{par}

@endnode

