    @{"New" link New}
    @{"Load ..." link Load}
    @{"Save" link Save}
    @{"Save as ..." link SaveAs}
    @{"Import..." link Import}
    @{"Export" link Export}
        @{"Graphic formats" link GfxTypes}
    @{"About ..." link Info}
    @{"Quit" link Quit}

  @{b}ARexx
    @{"Execute ARexx script ..." link StartARexx}
    @{"F1: ..." link FKey}
    @{"F2: ..." link FKey}
        .
        .
        .
    @{"F10: ..." link FKey}

  @{b}Settings@{ub}
    @{"Change settings..." link ChangeSettings}
    @{"Load settings..." link LoadSettings}
    @{"Save settings" link SaveSettings}
    @{"Save as settings..." link SaveAsSettings}

@endnode

@node New 

Clears the @{"input gadget" link Input} and the @{"Preview" link Preview}.@{par}

@{b}Warning:@{ub} This action cannot be made undone.

@endnode

@node Load

Opens a file requester in which a file can be chosen which should be loaded.@{par}
Only files which have the suffix .fml are shown there. It is appended
automatically by the @{"Save" link Save} function. If you wish to load an
ASCII file without this suffix, just clear the gadget "Pattern".@{par}

You can also use MathScript's AppWindow/AppIcon support. Simply drag an icon
of a formula over the @{"main window" link mainwin} or AppIcon (if iconified).

@endnode

@node Save 

Does the same as @{"Save as ..." link SaveAs}, except that if a file has been
loaded or saved before no file requester will pop up and the current file will
be used for saving.@{par}

The name of the current file is shown on the title bar.

@endnode

@node SaveAs "Save as"

This saves the current contents of the @{"input gadget" link Input} as a Formula
file, in order to reuse or modify the formula later on.@{par}
A file requester will be opened, in which a file can be chosen, which should
be used for saving.@{par}

All formulas saved with MathScript have the suffix .fml, in order to
distinguish them from regular text files.

@endnode

@node Import

When a formula is @{"exported" link Export} its formula description is included
into the graphics file. With this function it is possible to load it from
a previously exported formula.@{par}

If an exported file was modified in any way by another program, the formula
description may not be found. In this case you are able to search the whole
file for it.@{par}
For example a word processor may include an EPS file into an IFF file when
copying it into the clipboard. With this feature you can search the clipboard
file for the formula.@{par}

This feature is supported by all @{"graphics formats" link GfxTypes} except @{"EPS" link EPS}.
@endnode

@node Export 

This function saves the current formula as a graphics file which can be
loaded into other applications (word processors,DTP programs,...).@{par}

MathScript supports different @{"graphics formats" link GfxTypes} which are selectable
as submenu items.

@endnode

@node GfxTypes "Graphic formats"

In the current version MathScript supports the following formats:@{par}

@{code}
  @{"EPS" link EPS}
  @{"Binary EPS" link BinEPS}
  @{"IFF" link IFF}
  @{"TIFF" link TIFF}

@endnode

@node EPS

This format is the most popular vector graphic format. In opposition to bitmap
formats like the IFF-ILBM they have an excellent printing quality.@{par}

EPS means @{b}E@{ub}ncapsulated @{b}P@{ub}ost@{b}S@{ub}cript.@{par}
PostScript is a interpretative page describing language, which is known by
several laser printers. If you do not have such a printer, you are dependent
on the software, in which the formulas should be used. For example the word
processor "FinalWriter" is able to convert EPS files to Bitmaps so they can be
printed on regular printers..@{par}

This format contains only Ascii characters so it can be send directly to a
PostScript printer or displayed by a software interpreter like "Post".@{par}
If this is not neccessary you should use the variation @{"Binary EPS" link BinEPS}.@{par}

This format does not include the formula description, so the menu item
@{"Import" link Import} does not work with these files.

@endnode

@node BinEPS "Binary EPS"

This format contains the regular @{"EPS" link EPS} code and a bitmap in the
@{"TIFF" link TIFF} formatas a preview.

The advantage of this format against the pure Ascii @{"EPS" link EPS} is that it
can be easily shown on the monitor and printed out on non-PostScript printers.@{par}

@endnode

@node IFF

There is not much to say abaout the IFF-ILBM format, is it? ;)

Because it is a bitmap format you will not reach the printing quality of
(Binary) @{"EPS" link EPS} files.@{par}
On the other side it should be loadable by all graphic supporting programs.

@endnode

@node TIFF

The TIFF format is bitmap based.@{par}
It has not the importance on the Amiga like the @{"IFF" link IFF} format, but is was
needed for the @{"Binary EPS" link BinEPS} format.@{par}
Nevertheless it could be usefull when using MathScript formulas on other
computer systems because it is very widespread.

@endnode

@node Info "About"

Opens an window, in which there are informations about the program and me.

@endnode

@node Quit 

Quits the program.

@endnode

@node StartARexx "Execute ARexx script"

Opens a file requester in which an ARexx script can be chosen which should be
executed.@{par}
Detailled informations about the ARexx port of MathScript can be found under
@{"ARexx" link ARexx}.

@endnode

@node FKey "Function keys"

In the @{"Settings Window" link setwin} on the @{"ARexx page" link SetARexx} there are the
@{"Function keys gadgets" link SetFKey}.@{par}
If you have installed an ARexx scripts on a particular function key, you are
able to execute that script by selecting the corresponding menu item, too.

@endnode

@node ChangeSettings "Change settings"

This opens the @{"Settings Window" link setwin} in which MathScript's settings
can be changed.@{par}

@endnode

@node LoadSettings "Load settings"

You can load the settings out of a previously saved prefs file with this
menu item.

@endnode

@node SaveSettings "Save settings"

This will save your settings to be used next time.

@endnode

@node SaveAsSettings "Save as settings"

Selecting this menu item you are able to save the current settings into
any file.

@endnode

@node ARexx

With its ARexx port MathScript can be controlled from "outside" what means
without intervention of the user.@{par}

MathScript allocates for each running task ist own ARexx port.
The name of the first one is  @{b}"MATHSCRIPT.1"@{ub}, the second is called
@{b}"MATHSCRIPT.2@{ub} and so on.@{par}

An ARexx script can be started by MathScript with the menu item
@{"Execute ARexx script" link StartARexx}.@{par}

Arguments follow the standard Amiga ReadArgs() conventions.@{par}

Here is the list of all supported @{b}commands:@{ub}@{par}

@{"Clear" link Clear}@{par}
@{"Export" link rx_Export}@{par}
@{"GetARexxPrefs" link GetARexxPrefs}@{par}
@{"GetContents" link GetContents}@{par}
@{"GetDimensions" link rx_GetDim}@{par}
@{"GetExportPrefs" link GetExportPrefs}@{par}
@{"GetGeneralPrefs" link GetGeneralPrefs}@{par}
@{"GetPosition" link GetPosition}@{par}
@{"GetSystemPrefs" link GetSystemPrefs}@{par}
@{"GetZoom" link rx_GetZoom}@{par}
@{"Import" link rx_Import}@{par}
@{"Insert" link Insert}@{par}
@{"Load" link rx_Load}@{par}
@{"LoadPrefs" link rx_LoadPrefs}@{par}
@{"Preview" link rx_Preview}@{par}
@{"Requester" link Requester}@{par}
@{"Save" link rx_Save}@{par}
@{"SavePrefs" link rx_SavePrefs}@{par}
@{"SavePrefsAs" link rx_SavePrefsAs}@{par}
@{"ScreenToFront" link ScreenToFront}@{par}
@{"SetARexxPrefs" link SetARexxPrefs}@{par}
@{"SetContents" link SetContents}@{par}
@{"SetExportPrefs" link SetExportPrefs}@{par}
@{"SetGeneralPrefs" link SetGeneralPrefs}@{par}
@{"SetPosition" link SetPosition}@{par}
@{"SetSystemPrefs" link SetSystemPrefs}@{par}
@{"SetZoom" link rx_SetZoom}@{par}


@endnode

